{
  "answer": "The ghazal is Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 148 (\"Na tha kuch toh Khuda tha, kuch na hota toh Khuda hota\").[^1]\n\nIts opening paradox reads: \"When nothing was, then God would be; if nothing were, God still would be. / This state of being drowned me here; had I not been, what would there be?\"[^2]\n\nThe surreal severed-head couplet reads: \"So numb with grief, what should I dread if from my shoulders falls my head? / Were it not severed, it would be laid gently, grieving, on my knee.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 148, [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/148-na-tha-kuch-toh-khuda-tha-kuch-na-hota-toh-khuda-h/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 148, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/148-na-tha-kuch-toh-khuda-tha-kuch-na-hota-toh-khuda-h/translation/#p-1420db).\n\n[^3]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 148, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/148-na-tha-kuch-toh-khuda-tha-kuch-na-hota-toh-khuda-h/translation/#p-6f69a2).",
